The SFB understanding of women’s health should, in this case, extend beyond the provision of healthcare services (UNFPA, 2016; 4), and should explore other strategies for promoting positive societal attitudes towards abortion, including gender mainstreaming, access and availability of family planning (FP) services, awareness-raising and stigma reduction.
BURUNDI
In Burundi, 80 per cent of women who have ever had sex have ever used contraceptives, while only 29 per cent have ever used safe abortion care. However, these figures are likely to be over-estimated, as many women do not disclose details of their abortion histories to service providers. With abandonment of contraception as the main reason for having an abortion, family planning continues to be an important tool to prevent unwanted pregnancies, and promote space for safe and lawful post-abortion care. The intervention in Burundi is expected to increase knowledge, awareness, and accessibility to safe abortion information and services in three districts.
